Now I have both the tests and the production code. Here's the full audit.

---

## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 4 Critical · 2 High · 1 Medium · 0 Low**

This suite is systematically afflicted by **self-referential assertions** — the dominant pattern is `Assert.AreEqual(input, f(input))` where the input is chosen so `f` is a no-op. These tests give green coverage while verifying nothing.

---

### ✅ Positive Observations

Tests 1–2 (`Serialize_ThenDeserialize_ProducesOriginal`, `ToString_ParseBack_Identity`) are **legitimate round-trip tests**. Serialization/deserialization and `ToString`/`Parse` are genuine identity operations, and the assertions are meaningful.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–42) — Self-referential assertion

The input `"alice"` is **already normalized** (lowercase, no whitespace). `Normalize()` does `.Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`, so the output equals the input trivially. This would pass even if `Normalize` were `return name;`.

```csharp
// BEFORE — tautological: input is already normalized
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// FIX — use input that requires transformation, assert against a literal
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize("  ALICE  ");
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

#### 2. `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 56–61) — Self-referential assertion

Asserts `user.Name == user.GetDisplayName()`. Production code: `GetDisplayName() => Name`. This is asserting a property against the method that returns that same property — `Assert.AreEqual(x.Name, x.Name)` in disguise. The test name says "FormattedName" but it would **pass even if formatting were completely absent**.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts property against itself via method
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// FIX — assert against a known expected literal
// (If GetDisplayName should format, e.g. "Alice (30)", assert that.
//  If it should just return the name, assert the literal.)
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);
```

#### 3. `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 71–77) — Self-referential / always-true assertion

Input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase. `.ToUpper()` on an uppercase string is a no-op. This test can never fail.

```csharp
// BEFORE — input is already uppercase, assertion is trivially true
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// FIX — use mixed-case input, assert against a literal
var result = "hello".ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

#### 4. `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 46–53) — Lossy round-trip hiding data loss

The mapping is **lossy by design**: `ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email`; `ToEntity` drops `Age` and zeros out `Id`. A round-trip can never reconstruct the original. With the current production code, this test would actually **fail** (`entity.Id` is 1, `backToEntity.Id` is 0; `entity.Email` is `"a@b.com"`, `backToEntity.Email` is `""`). This means it is either never run or the production code has diverged. Either way, the pattern is wrong — each mapping direction should be tested independently.

```csharp
// BEFORE — lossy round-trip that either fails or hides data loss
var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
var backToEntity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Id, backToEntity.Id);          // 1 vs 0!
Assert.AreEqual(entity.FullName, backToEntity.FullName);
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Email, backToEntity.Email);     // "a@b.com" vs ""!

// FIX — test each direction in isolation against literal expected values
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age);        // document that Age is defaulted
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);      // document that Id is defaulted
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email);  // document that Email is defaulted
}
```

---

### 🟠 High — Likely To Cause Pain

#### 5. `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64–69) — Missing coverage of actual validation

The assertion `input == result` is technically correct (the validator returns its input for valid emails), but this test only covers the trivial pass-through path. The **actual validation behavior** — rejecting invalid input with `ArgumentException` — is completely untested.

```csharp
// ADD — test the real validation behavior
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_MissingAtSign_ThrowsArgumentException()
